<TITLE> European stocks fall as US subprime worry grows </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 FRANKFURT, July 11 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - European shares opened lower on Wednesday as growing concern over the US subprime mortgage market caused US and Asian stocks to tumble and as the oil price hovered near an 11-months high. Among major movers, BSkyB rose 2.3 percent after saying it had added 90,000 net new customers in the three months to the end of June, up 17 percent year-on-year. The pan-European FTSEurofirst 300 index fell 0.7 percent to 1,595.09 points at 0711 GMT, its lowest in over a week. "I think there are three elements to look at today. The concern over the subprime mortgage market and what it might cause. Secondly, the oil price and the third point is the profit warning from Home Depot showing how weak the US domestic economy might be," said Justin Urquhart Stewart of 7 Investment Management. "I can't see any particular reason to take a positive stand," he added. Britain's FTSE 100 slipped 0.5 percent, while Germany's DAX dropped 1.1 percent and France's CAC 40 eased 0.8 perce
